ce:section.ce:para:
The preparation of F-SiNPs was accomplished through hydrothermal treatment of 2-hydroxyphenylboronic acid and 3-(2-aminoethylamino) propyltriethoxysilane) at 180 °C. After purification through dialysis, the original F-SiNPs solution exhibited dark brown in visible light. And weak yellow-green fluorescence was observed under 365 nm UV light (
                           Figure S1
                        ), indicating that the F-SiNPs were successfully fabricated. In the UV–vis absorption of spectrum of F-SiNPs, an obvious peak centered at about 430 nm was noticed (
                           Figure S1
                        ), which was corresponding to the excitation spectrum of F-SiNPs (Fig. 2

                        A). At the same time, the fluorescence emission spectra of the obtained F-SiNPs at different excitation wavelengths ranging from 350 nm to 450 nm were investigated. The fluorescence intensity varied with increasing the fluorescence excitation wavelength from 350 to 450 nm. And the fluorescence intensity at 515 nm was the highest when the excitation wavelength was 430 nm (Fig. 2
                        B), which was consisted with the UV–vis absorption spectrum and excitation spectrum of F-SiNPs. Therefore, 430 nm and 515 nm were respectively selected as the maximum excitation wavelength and maximum emission wavelength for the following experiments. Moreover, the peak position of fluorescence emission spectra displayed a slight red-shift (
                           Figure S2
                        ), revealing that the as prepared F-SiNPs possessed weak excitation dependent emission properties.

The relative quantum yield of the F-SiNPs was calculated to be about 4.8% by utilizing rhodamine 6G (95%) solution as a reference [26]. And the photostability of F-SiNPs was accessed by continuous irradiation of 365 nm UV light. After irradiation for 15 min, the fluorescence intensity of F-SiNPs decreased by 23%, indicating that the photostability should be improved (
                           Figure S3
                        ). However, the fluorescence intensity of the F-SiNPs remained unchanged after continuous scanning for 30 times at the excitation of 430 nm, revealing that the F-SiNPs could be fabricated into fluorescent nanosensors (
                           Figure S4
                        ). The stability of F-SiNPs in high concentrations salt solution was further investigated. Amazingly, the fluorescence intensity of F-SiNPs at 515 nm only declined 9% in the 1.0 M of NaCl solution, demonstrating the excellent salt tolerance ability of the F-SiNPs (
                           Figure S5
                        ). The fluorescence lifetime of F-SiNPs was measured to be about 4.1892 ns (
                           Figure S6
                        ), which was comparable to that of other F-SiNPs [27]. And the short lifetime revealed that the fluorescence mechanism of the F-SiNPs may be attributed to the radiative recombination [28].

Under the optimum experimental conditions, we further exploited the fluorescent detection of S2- by combining DTNB and F-SiNPs. We first studied the effect of S2-, DTNB and the mixture of DTNB and S2- on the fluorescence intensity of F-SiNPs. It was easily observed that S2- and DTNB displayed negligible impact on the fluorescence intensity of F-SiNPs. However, the mixture of DTNB and S2- caused an obvious decline of the fluorescence intensity, demonstrating that the F-SiNPs could be employed for fluorescence turn-off assay of S2- (
                           Figure S11
                        ). We then accessed the effect of incubation time on the fluorescence intensity of F-SiNPs. Upon adding S2- and DTNB to the F-SiNPs solution, the fluorescence intensity at 515 nm rapidly declined to the minimum, and no further changed, demonstrating that the TNB yielded from the reaction between S2- and DTNB could quickly repress the fluorescence of F-SiNPs (
                           Figure S12
                        ). Therefore, rapid fluorescent detection of S2- could be accomplished by using F-SiNPs and DTNB.

To evaluate the practicality of the proposed method, the concentration of S2- in tap and lake water was measured. Before the experiments, no S2- was found in tap and lake water (
                           Figure S14
                        ). Afterwards, S2- was spiked with tap and lake water, respectively. As exhibited in Table S2, the found values were close to the added values of S2-, and the relative standard deviations (RSD) were less than 1.11%, demonstrating the good potential of the developed approach for sensing S2- in real samples.
